                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>Q. When was the house searched?</p>
               <p>Clark. A month after she made the first application.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17710515-21-person312">
                  James
                   Dennis
               <interp inst="t17710515-21-person312" type="surname" value="Dennis"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person312" type="given" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person312" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I served the writ upon her about an action being brought by one Mr. Brase. She flew into a passion and said she knew Byerman's life was in her hands for coining money. I said, young woman be very careful.</p>
               <p>Q. What is that man?</p>
               <p>Dennis. A relation to Mr. Byerman.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17710515-21-person313">
                  Henry
                   Clements
               <interp inst="t17710515-21-person313" type="surname" value="Clements"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person313" type="given" value="Henry"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person313" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I keep Hoxton Town Coffee-house. I have known the prisoner four or five years. I never heard any bad character of him. I dealt with him, I never took any bad money of him, to my knowledge.</p>
               <p>Q. Had you any bad money ever offered to you by them?</p>
               <p>Clements. Not that I know of.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17710515-21-person314">
                  Elizabeth
                   Powell
               <interp inst="t17710515-21-person314" type="surname" value="Powell"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person314" type="given" value="Elizabeth"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person314" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live with Mr. Byerman.</p>
               <p>Q. What character does he bear?</p>
               <p>Powell. I never heard any harm of him; he paid me honestly when I came away.</p>
               <p>Q. When did you quit his service?</p>
               <p>Powell. About six months ago; not quite six months ago.</p>
               <p>Q. Who succeeded you?</p>
               <p>Powell. A little young woman that applied here.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17710515-21-person315">
                  Mary
                   Bell
               <interp inst="t17710515-21-person315" type="surname" value="Bell"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person315" type="given" value="Mary"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person315" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Town Ditch; I take in washing.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you know Mr. Byerman?</p>
               <p>Bell. Yes.</p>
               <p>Q. What character has he?</p>
               <p>Bell. A very good one.</p>
               <p>Q. Had you any dealings with him?</p>
               <p>Bell. Yes; I have taken four or five pounds at a time of him; I never took any bad money of him, nor saw any.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17710515-21-person316">
                  Samuel
                   Stiff
               <interp inst="t17710515-21-person316" type="surname" value="Stiff"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person316" type="given" value="Samuel"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person316" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a butcher; I live at Hoxton Town; I have known the prisoner eight or ten years; I have had dealings with the family fourteen or fifteen months; I never took any bad money of them to my knowledge.</p>
               <p>- Hume. I am a cheesemonger in Shoreditch; I served the prisoner with butter and cheese; I never heard any thing bad of the prisoner; nor never took any bad money of him to my knowledge.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17710515-21-person317">
                  John
                   Warner
               <interp inst="t17710515-21-person317" type="surname" value="Warner"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person317" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person317" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a tallow-chandler, and live in Shoreditch; I have but little acquaintance with the prisoner; the father dealt with me six or seven years; I never took any of the son's money.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17710515-21-person318">
                  William
                   Clarke
               <interp inst="t17710515-21-person318" type="surname" value="Clarke"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person318" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person318" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I have been married eleven years to that woman, pointing at 
               <persName id="t17710515-21-person319">
                  Sarah
                   Clarke
               <interp inst="t17710515-21-person319" type="surname" value="Clarke"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person319" type="given" value="Sarah"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person319" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17710515-21-person320">
                  John
                   Clarke
               <interp inst="t17710515-21-person320" type="surname" value="Clarke"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person320" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person320" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I had a warrant to search the house; I found nothing.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you hear 
               <persName id="t17710515-21-person321">
                  Sarah
                   Clarke
               <interp inst="t17710515-21-person321" type="surname" value="Clarke"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person321" type="given" value="Sarah"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person321" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             describe the fly at Sir John Fielding's?</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17710515-21-person322">
                  Clarke
                   Yes
               <interp inst="t17710515-21-person322" type="surname" value="Yes"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person322" type="given" value="Clarke"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person322" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            ; the manner in which she described it was not like such a thing; she gave no account of any press; I served my time to a button maker.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you think that silver could be melted in an iron ladle?</p>
               <p>Clarke. That is a matter of doubt.</p>
               <p>Q. What do you think of tutenage?</p>
               <p>Clarke. I can't tell: I don't think it could be melted in an iron ladle without a furnace.</p>
               <p>Q. Is tutenage softer or harder than silver?</p>
               <p>Clarke. I rather think it softer; if there is an air furnace it would melt of itself?</p>
               <p>Q. Are you sure it would not melt without a furnace, or being blown under?</p>
               <p>Clarke. Yes.</p>

               <p>Q. Would tutenage put into a hot coal fire melt?</p>
               <p>Clarke. I should think not; I should think it would not melt without the fire being blown under.</p>
               <p>Q. You never heard of this metal being melted in an iron ladle?</p>
               <p>Clarke. No; nor any mechanic whatever, I am sure.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="177105150039"></xptr>Council for the Crown. Is there no putting something among the metal to soften it?</p>
               <p>Clarke. I cannot say; I think tutenage will not melt without a draught, or blowing under it.</p>
               <p>Court. Tutenage is a mixed metal, I think?</p>
               <p>Clarke. I believe a substance of itself.</p>
               <p>Q. Is it not a sort of copper?</p>
               <p>Clarke. They call it white copper.</p>
               <p>Q. What do you think of this coin that has been produced?</p>
               <p>Clarke. It appears to be silver alloyed with copper.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17710515-21-person323">
                  Rebecca
                   Burn
               <interp inst="t17710515-21-person323" type="surname" value="Burn"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person323" type="given" value="Rebecca"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-person323" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I have know him seven or eight years. I live in Red-lion court, Grub-street. I am a buckle-chase maker. I never heard any bad character of him.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you know where he was on Ash Wednesday?</p>
               <p>Burn. I cannot say; I was at Mr. Byerman's to spend the evening; he was not there: I went there a little after, and staid there all the evening: I asked for him, and he was gone out. I was in the parlour and the kitchen; Mrs. Byerman was in the parlour.</p>
               <p>Q. Was old Mrs. Byaman at home?</p>
               <p>Burn. No when I first went.</p>
               <p>Q. What time did she come home?</p>
               <p>Burn. Some time in the evening; I cannot tell exactly what time.</p>
               <p>Cross Examination.</p>
               <p>Q. How came you to recollect the day?</p>
               <p>Burn. My child lay dead at the time.</p>
               <p>Q. Was it hurried?</p>
               <p>Burn. No.</p>
               <p>Q. What did you go to pay a visit when your child lay dead?</p>
               <p>Burn. Yes; I went there almost every day.</p>
               <p>Q. Where did you live?</p>
               <p>Burn. A whole week at my mother's.</p>
               <p>Q. You did not see him come in, but saw him when he was in the house?</p>
               <p>Burn. I was in the parlour when he came in.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you hear him come in?</p>
               <p>Burn. I saw him come in.</p>
               <p>Q. You did not see him come in at?</p>

               <p>Burn. No.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you hear him knock at the door?</p>
               <p>Burn. No; I heard the bell ring.</p>
               <p>Q. Was that before dinner, or after?</p>
               <p>Burn. After; I was in the house before dinner: I went to dine with my mother, at the next door; they asked me to stay dinner.</p>
               <p>Q. Who?</p>
               <p>Burn. Mrs. Byerman herself.</p>
               <p>Q. You said they?</p>
               <p>Burn. It was Mrs. Byerman. I went in, between twelve and one, and she asked me to dine. I went home and dined, and came in again about two. My child died the tenth of February. I had been a week before at my mother's.</p>
               <p>Q. When did you see him come home?</p>
               <p>Burn. Between nine and ten at night.</p>
               <p>Q. He was not at home from that time?</p>
               <p>Burn. No; I asked his mother for him; she said he was not at home.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17710515-21-verdict119" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17710515-21-verdict119" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               Acquitted
            </rs>.</p>
